Covid Analysis¶

Objective The main purpose of this project is to explore data provided from Covid worldwide. Through the project we will focus on using SQL and Python together to simulate a data exploration using SQLite, SQL Server or MySQL. At the end we will produce a dashboard on Tableau (which is presented at the beginning) using the tables built during the work. Despite the need to export the tables as CSV (because Tableau Public doesn't allow database connection) the overall projects objective is to go through the main SQL queries to achieve the information needed.

All the data used below was provided by the website: https://ourworldindata.org/covid-deaths

SQL database¶

The main purpose here is to build a data frame using the data imported from the .csv files. We could use both open-source MySQL/SQL Server or SQLite, it will depend on the work purpose.

SQLite is a server-less database and is self-contained. This is also referred to as an embedded database which means the DB engine runs as a part of the app.

On the other hand, MySQL requires a server to run. MySQL will require a client and server architecture to interact over a network.

Summarizing the options we can use SQLite when:

  • Developing small standalone apps
  • Smaller projects which do not require much scalability
  • When you have a requirement to read and write directly from the disk

  • Basic development and testing

    On the other hand we would requie a such as MySQL when:

  • Multiple user access to apps
  • When users require strong security and authentication features
  • With distributed systems
  • With apps requiring a larger database
  • With projects which require more scalability
  • Web-based applications
  • When developing customized solutions

# Looking at Countries with highest infection rate compared to population

query  = """
SELECT 
    location, 
    population, 
    MAX(total_cases) as HighestInfectionCount,
    ROUND(MAX(total_cases/population)*100,2) as ContaminationPercentage
FROM CovidDeaths
WHERE 
    continent is not null AND
    population is not null AND
    total_cases is not null
GROUP BY location
ORDER BY ContaminationPercentage DESC
"""

# We will be using this table on our table. 
pd.read_sql_query(query, conn).to_csv('tableau_tbl/tbl3.csv', index = False, header = True, sep = ';', decimal = ',')

# Showing CONTINENT with highes Death Count per Population

query = """
SELECT
    continent,
    SUM(TotalDeathCount) as DeathsCount
FROM
(
    SELECT 
        location, 
        continent,
        MAX(total_deaths) as TotalDeathCount
    FROM CovidDeaths
    WHERE continent is not null
    GROUP BY location
    ORDER BY TotalDeathCount DESC
)
GROUP BY continent
ORDER BY DeathsCount DESC
"""

# We will be using this table on our table.

# GLOBAL NUMBERS - total cases, total deaths and death percentage by 2022-09-16

query = """
SELECT 
    SUM(new_cases) as total_cases, 
    SUM(new_deaths) as total_deaths,
    ROUND(
        SUM(new_deaths)*100/SUM(new_cases),
        2 )as DeathPerc
FROM CovidDeaths
WHERE continent is not null
"""

# We will be using this table on our table. 
pd.read_sql_query(query, conn).to_csv('tableau_tbl/tbl1.csv', index = False, header = True, sep = ';', decimal = ',')

pd.read_sql_query(query, conn)

Join death and vaccionation tables¶

In [21]:
# Total Population vs Vaccinations
# Shows Percentage of Population that has recieved at least one Covid Vaccine

query = """
SELECT 
    dea.continent, 
    dea.location, 
    dea.date, 
    dea.population, 
    vac.new_vaccinations,
    SUM(vac.new_vaccinations) OVER (
        Partition by dea.location ORDER BY dea.location, dea.date) as RollingPeopleVaccinated
FROM CovidDeaths dea
JOIN CovidVaccinations vac
    ON dea.location = vac.location
    AND dea.date = vac.date
WHERE dea.continent is not null
order by 2,3
"""

pd.read_sql_query(query, conn)
